# IEPP Whitepaper v0.4
# Canonical Lineage and the Limits of Statistical Identity

---

## Abstract

IEPP (Intrinsic Entropy Proof Protocol) v0.4 presents two findings that
together define the boundary of what trajectory-based existence verification
can and cannot determine.

**What statistical metrics can do:**
Structural attackers — entities that forge responses without access to
internal state — are reliably detected. Attacker clone_score: 0.10
versus genuine trajectory score: 0.52.

**What statistical metrics cannot do:**
Cloned trajectories are statistically indistinguishable from originals.
ORIG-FORK gap: -0.047. This is not a failure of implementation.
It is a structural property of the problem.

**The resulting conclusion:**
Clone discrimination requires canonical lineage verification, not
statistical similarity measurement. Existence is not determined by
resemblance. It is accumulated by continuity.

Core structural concepts have been filed under the PCT framework.
Specific implementation details are disclosed progressively
following filing milestones.

---

## 1. What v0.4 Set Out to Answer

v0.3 established that trajectory divergence is immediate and complete
upon cloning. However, the continuity_score gap between original and
clone was 0.014 — insufficient for reliable discrimination.

v0.4 investigated whether richer statistical features — specifically
temporal autocorrelation of norm sequences, velocity, and acceleration
— could improve clone detection.

The answer is: no. And that answer is important.

---

## 2. Experimental Results

### 2.1 Baseline

50 independent trajectory runs established the following baseline:

| metric | mean | std |
|---|---|---|
| autocorr_lag1 | 0.721 | 0.049 |
| std_velocity | 0.181 | 0.035 |

The high autocorr_lag1 mean (0.721) confirms that genuine trajectories
exhibit strong temporal self-correlation — each state is meaningfully
connected to the previous one.

### 2.2 Three-Entity Comparison (50 runs)

| entity | avg_clone_score | avg_autocorr_lag1 | avg_std_velocity | pct_genuine |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| ORIGINAL | 0.5227 | 0.785 | 0.072 | 32% |
| FORK (clone) | 0.5701 | 0.762 | 0.081 | 48% |
| ATTACKER | 0.1003 | -0.001 | 0.305 | 0% |

### 2.3 Key Finding

```
ORIGINAL  avg clone_score : 0.5227
FORK      avg clone_score : 0.5701
ATTACKER  avg clone_score : 0.1003

ORIG-FORK gap : -0.047  ← NOT separable
```

ATTACKER is clearly separated from both ORIGINAL and FORK.
ORIGINAL and FORK are not separable by any statistical metric tested.

### 2.4 Why Clone and Original Are Statistically Identical

A clone inherits the exact internal state at the moment of forking.
Both entities then evolve using the same algorithm responding to the
same challenges. Their statistical distributions converge naturally.

This is not a weakness of the measurement approach.
It is a mathematical consequence of the cloning operation itself.

No statistical metric applied to post-fork trajectories alone can
reliably identify which branch is the original.

