## 4. Scope and Layer Boundaries

IEPP defines the measurement and verification layer.
It does not define policy, governance, or canonical selection.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Layer 3: Governance / Policy           │
│  Who is canonical? Dispute resolution.  │
│  → Decided by users, institutions,      │
│    trust frameworks                     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 2: Application                   │
│  Canonical selection, branch management │
│  → Decided by platforms, services       │
├─────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Layer 1: IEPP Protocol                 │
│  continuity verification                │
│  divergence detection                   │
│  lineage auditability                   │
│  → This is what IEPP provides           │
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

This boundary is intentional, not a limitation.

TCP/IP does not determine which data is correct.
DNS does not determine which domain is trustworthy.
IEPP does not determine which trajectory is canonical.

IEPP provides the measurement.
The application decides what to do with it.

