## 6. Future Vision: The Genesis Registry

*This section is speculative. It describes a possible future direction,
not a current implementation.*

Today, origin is established by trusted institutions:
patent offices record invention priority,
notaries record document authenticity,
timestamp authorities record digital creation moments.

As AI governance frameworks mature, a new kind of origin registry
may become necessary — one designed specifically for AI entities.

A possible structure:

```
AI entity created
      ↓
Registers first trajectory commitment
with a designated Genesis Registry
      ↓
Registry records: entity_id, R_0, timestamp, context
      ↓
All subsequent continuity verified against this anchor
```

This would function as a birth record for AI entities.

IEPP provides the continuity proof.
The Genesis Registry provides the origin anchor.
Together, they form a complete existence verification stack:

```
Genesis Registry  →  "this entity was created at time T"
IEPP              →  "this entity has existed continuously since T"
```

The registry itself need not be centralized.
It could be distributed, institutional, or AI-native —
an AI system designated to witness and record the genesis
of other AI entities.

The policy questions — who operates the registry, what
constitutes valid registration, how disputes are resolved —
remain outside IEPP's scope. They belong to the governance layer.

What IEPP contributes is the lower layer:
a verifiable, forgery-resistant continuity record
that any registry can anchor to.

